RT @MarkWarner Today we remember the lives lost following the deadly rally that occurred a year ago in Charlottesville, when a group of white nationalists came to a peaceful Virginia town seeking to use hate and division to incite violence against fair-minded, innocent civilians.
RT @EastBayTimes California Fires: Yosemite Valley to re-open Tuesday morning https://trib.al/sBAO2iW

We can honor Heather Heyer’s memory by standing up to all forms of oppression and bigotry in this country - racism, sexism, homophobia, xenophobia and religious intolerance. All of us must do our part in creating a just society.

The next day, the white supremacists and Neo-Nazis marched again but this time thousands of protesters showed up to stand up to their hatred and bigotry. Countless people were injured standing up to hate and and one person, Heather Heyer, was killed.

One year ago today, a few students with nothing but a “VA Students Act Against White Supremacy” banner courageously stood up to hundreds of white supremacists and Neo-Nazis who had them surrounded while marching in defense of a Confederate statue in Charlottesville.
